Now consider the complexity of recognizing contact graphs of congruent sphere packings in ${\mathbb{E}}^{3}$. Just like its 2-dimensional analogue, Hlin\v{e}n\'{y} \cite{Hl} showed the 3-dimensional problem to be NP-hard by reduction from 3-SAT. In fact, the same is true in four dimensions \cite{Hl}.

\begin{theorem}\label{3-hard}
The problem of recognizing contact graphs of unit sphere packings in ${\mathbb{E}}^3$ (resp., ${\mathbb{E}}^4$) is NP-hard.
\end{theorem}













